the intestines,

92
00:03:20,218 --> 00:03:21,701
force hemorrhages,

93
00:03:21,786 --> 00:03:23,181
intussusception.

94
00:03:23,266 --> 00:03:26,062
- Even a strangulated bowel.
- They can also do this.

95
00:03:27,970 --> 00:03:29,180
Cool, right?

96
00:03:30,118 --> 00:03:32,210
But you only swallowed
one magnet, didn't you?

97
00:03:32,325 --> 00:03:33,546
Mm.

98
00:03:33,630 --> 00:03:35,445
So that should pass
in a few hours.

99
00:03:35,777 --> 00:03:37,484
Turns out you don't need me.

100
00:03:37,881 --> 00:03:39,931
Uh, in case you haven't
noticed,

101
00:03:40,016 --> 00:03:42,164
we have a full ED of patients
who need your help.

102
00:03:42,248 --> 00:03:43,252
Where do you think
you're going?

103
00:03:43,336 --> 00:03:44,862
I always show up
when I'm paged,

104
00:03:44,947 --> 00:03:47,148
but I only stay
when I'm needed.

105
00:03:52,891 --> 00:03:54,871
<i>Dr. Gilmore to Pediatrics.</i>

106
00:03:54,956 --> 00:03:56,766
<i>Dr. Gilmore to Pediatrics.</i>

107
00:03:56,867 --> 00:03:58,969
Should I go
for the energy drink

108
00:03:59,134 --> 00:04:00,269
or the protein bar?

109
00:04:00,406 --> 00:04:01,867
Why would you need energy?

110
00:04:01,952 --> 00:04:04,078
You seem intent on doing
virtually nothing.

111
00:04:05,429 --> 00:04:07,023
So you vote protein bar.

112
00:04:07,229 --> 00:04:08,625
I know that trauma surgeons

113
00:04:08,709 --> 00:04:10,594
like to play the aloof cowboy,
but that's not...

114
00:04:10,679 --> 00:04:12,118
That's not how
you do things here.

115
00:04:12,203 --> 00:04:13,947
- No, yes, it's not.
- I know.

116
00:04:14,061 --> 00:04:15,393
Don't you think I researched
this place

117
00:04:15,477 --> 00:04:16,477
before I took the job?

118
00:04:16,562 --> 00:04:18,351
Then you should also know
Max's motto.

119
00:04:18,436 --> 00:04:20,828
"How can I help?"
Yeah, that's catchy.

120
00:04:21,662 --> 00:04:24,242
It's words that we live by.
Everybody chips in.

121
00:04:24,333 --> 00:04:27,117
- Everybody helps.
- Right now I am helping.

122
00:04:28,705 --> 00:04:30,391
By eating a protein bar.

123
00:04:30,507 --> 00:04:33,165
Hm. Duty calls.

124
00:04:33,366 --> 00:04:34,883
Well, maybe.

125
00:04:40,836 --> 00:04:42,039
So what you got?

126
00:04:42,124 --> 00:04:44,227
Lucas Jarvis.
Nail gun mishap.

127
00:04:44,312 --> 00:04:45,680
It slipped.

128
00:04:45,788 --> 00:04:47,445
Well, Mr. Jarvis,
you're very lucky.

129
00:04:47,530 --> 00:04:48,664
This is lucky?

130
00:04:48,749 --> 00:04:50,319
Well, the fact that your new
nail appendage

131
00:04:50,403 --> 00:04:52,453
missed the bone in every one
of your fingers is.

132
00:04:52,586 --> 00:04:54,105
You know what?

133
00:04:54,189 --> 00:04:55,359
Don't you dare.

134
00:04:55,444 --> 00:04:57,078
- I'm thinking Dr...
- Turan.

135
00:04:57,163 --> 00:04:58,428
Dr. Turan here gets
to practice

136
00:04:58,513 --> 00:04:59,675
her nail extraction skills.

137
00:04:59,760 --> 00:05:01,259
Now, a little numbing agent

138
00:05:01,344 --> 00:05:02,626
and some gentle retrograde
pressure,

139
00:05:02,710 --> 00:05:03,715
and that sucker should
come right out.

140
00:05:03,799 --> 00:05:05,020
- Dr. Shin...
- You got this?

141
00:05:05,105 --> 00:05:06,312
Yeah.

142
00:05:06,985 --> 00:05:08,337
- Dr. Shin!
- Mm?

143
00:05:08,421 --> 00:05:09,686
Where are you going?

144
00:05:09,858 --> 00:05:11,094
Nap time.

145
00:05:15,254 --> 00:05:16,843
I don't want to hear it.
My friend is sick,

146
00:05:16,927 --> 00:05:18,562
another is gone,
this hospital is slammed,

147
00:05:18,646 --> 00:05:20,014
and I'm gonna need you
to be a team player

148
00:05:20,098 --> 00:05:21,343
for once,
do you understand?

149
00:05:21,428 --> 00:05:22,394
I'm always a team player.

150
00:05:22,478 --> 00:05:23,709
Kit Brower, 25.

151
00:05:23,794 --> 00:05:25,350
Multiple lacs
from a large explosion

152
00:05:25,435 --> 00:05:26,922
- at his home.
- What exploded?

153
00:05:27,141 --> 00:05:28,359
What's that smell?

154
00:05:28,444 --> 00:05:29,866
I make beer.

155
00:05:29,983 --> 00:05:31,718
My fermenting vat...

156
00:05:31,803 --> 00:05:33,106
Book an OR right now.

157
00:05:34,272 --> 00:05:35,561
Grab a side.

158
00:05:36,588 --> 00:05:38,811
Nurse, I need two units
of O-neg on a bear-hugger.

159
00:05:38,896 --> 00:05:41,109
Uh. Hold on, the entire wing
is contaminated.

160
00:05:41,194 --> 00:05:43,827
No more surgeries until we can
disinfect every OR.

161
00:05:44,030 --> 00:05:45,330
Hey, welcome to New Amsterdam.

162
00:05:45,414 --> 00:05:47,538
Oh, yeah.
Great place.

163
00:05:47,623 --> 00:05:49,290
But look, he needs surgery
right now.

164
00:05:49,375 --> 00:05:51,421
How about an ICU?
Attendant's in quarantine.

165
00:05:52,876 --> 00:05:54,973
I got a place in mind.
We got to turn around.

166
00:05:55,058 --> 00:05:56,079
Thanks.

167
00:06:01,430 --> 00:06:02,478
You guys need something here?

168
00:06:02,562 --> 00:06:03,914
Yeah, we're commandeering
your rig.

169
00:06:03,998 --> 00:06:05,350
Help me get him in.
Wait, where are we going?

170
00:06:05,434 --> 00:06:07,004
Nowhere... we're doing
the surgery right here.

171
00:06:07,088 --> 00:06:09,050
Grab an OR tray and any
supplies you need.

172
00:06:12,887 --> 00:06:14,038
You in?

173
00:06:23,500 --> 00:06:24,678
This is trouble.

174
00:06:24,777 --> 00:06:26,515
When the glass tank exploded,

175
00:06:26,600 --> 00:06:28,069
it blew apart
the housing cabinet,

176
00:06:28,153 --> 00:06:31,507
pieces of which are all over
Kip's abdomen.

177
00:06:31,591 --> 00:06:33,248
If wood doesn't show up
on an X-ray.

178
00:06:33,332 --> 00:06:35,093
How are we gonna find
all the splinters?

179
00:06:35,945 --> 00:06:37,350
BP's dropping.

180
00:06:37,732 --> 00:06:39,772
Turn off all the lights
and cover all the windows.

181
00:06:42,350 --> 00:06:44,014
Now, flip that switch
to your right.

182
00:06:45,974 --> 00:06:49,110
Certain types of hardwood
turn fluorescent in blacklight.

183
00:06:49,195 --> 00:06:50,468
This ambulance has a UV light

184
00:06:50,553 --> 00:06:52,049
to keep infection
under control.

185
00:06:52,133 --> 00:06:53,268
Are you just gonna sit there?

186
00:06:53,352 --> 00:06:55,382
Everybody chips in,
everybody helps, right?

187
00:07:00,905 --> 00:07:02,155
Ready to drive now?

188
00:07:03,959 --> 00:07:05,410
You know, when I saw
the shards of wood,

189
00:07:05,494 --> 00:07:07,569
I honestly didn't think
he was gonna make it.

190
00:07:09,780 --> 00:07:11,038
What are you saying?

191
00:07:11,123 --> 00:07:12,472
I'm saying...

192
00:07:15,051 --> 00:07:16,405
Just what I said.

193
00:07:16,490 --> 00:07:18,293
Oh, okay.

194
00:07:18,378 --> 00:07:20,949
'Cause, you know, that kinda
sounded like a compliment.

195
00:07:21,280 --> 00:07:23,460
Would you like a gold star
on your report card?

196
00:07:23,545 --> 00:07:25,115
No.

197
00:07:25,371 --> 00:07:26,822
But if you're gonna
compliment me,

198
00:07:26,907 --> 00:07:28,346
it should sound
like a compliment.

199
00:07:28,811 --> 00:07:30,392
It was implied.

200
00:07:30,718 --> 00:07:32,968
Despite the fact that you took
a job in a public hospital

201
00:07:33,053 --> 00:07:34,163
and then refused to help.

202
00:07:36,270 --> 00:07:38,094
I didn't take the job
to help out everyone.

203
00:07:38,179 --> 00:07:40,366
I took the job
to save trauma victims.

204
00:07:41,617 --> 00:07:43,937
If a patient who needs
a trauma surgeon rolls up,

205
00:07:44,022 --> 00:07:45,663
I need to be
at the top of my game.

206
00:07:46,031 --> 00:07:48,104
And that may require
a shower or a nap

207
00:07:48,189 --> 00:07:49,975
or a protein bar,

208
00:07:50,060 --> 00:07:52,282
but whatever it takes,
I'm gonna do it,

209
00:07:52,367 --> 00:07:54,139
because I need to be ready.

210
00:07:55,155 --> 00:07:57,014
Self-care saves lives.

211
00:07:58,127 --> 00:08:00,959
Might not be the New Amsterdam
way, but...

212
00:08:01,435 --> 00:08:02,566
it's my way.

213
00:08:04,901 --> 00:08:06,077
What?

214
00:08:08,209 --> 00:08:09,882
Nothing, um...

215
00:08:11,560 --> 00:08:13,460
that makes perfect sense.

216
00:08:14,433 --> 00:08:15,671
But?

217
00:08:16,348 --> 00:08:19,507
But I save lives
every day too.

218
00:08:20,243 --> 00:08:21,820
And without naps.

219
00:08:44,370 --> 00:08:47,680
It was totally packed.
I mean, every seat was taken,

220
00:08:48,090 --> 00:08:50,298
but I desperately wanted
the aisle.

221
00:08:50,382 --> 00:08:51,786
So I swapped with her

222
00:08:51,871 --> 00:08:54,301
and endured the horrific middle
seat like a proper gentleman.

223
00:08:54,386 --> 00:08:57,465
And the rest as they say
is history.

224
00:08:59,828 --> 00:09:01,612
So how 'bout you?
How'd you two meet?

225
00:09:03,989 --> 00:09:07,129
Uh, that is a very
funny story actually,

226
00:09:07,214 --> 00:09:10,129
because I work for the, uh,
Yankees.

227
00:09:11,903 --> 00:09:13,908
Don't be modest, babe.

228
00:09:14,281 --> 00:09:16,043
He's the general manager.

229
00:09:16,128 --> 00:09:19,205
And I, believe it or not...
I worked for the Mets.

230
00:09:19,290 --> 00:09:21,364
The Mets.
And she's their general manager.

231
00:09:21,449 --> 00:09:22,637
Wait.
Seriously?

232
00:09:22,722 --> 00:09:24,263
Yeah, I know.
It's kind of hard to believe,

233
00:09:24,347 --> 00:09:25,536
- but it's...
- We met at

234
00:09:25,621 --> 00:09:26,931
- a General Managers Convention.
- That's-yeah...

235
00:09:27,015 --> 00:09:28,427
Wait, I didn't even know
those were a thing.

236
00:09:28,511 --> 00:09:29,661
Oh, yeah.
No, no, no.

237
00:09:29,746 --> 00:09:30,907
We don't call it inside
baseball for nothing.

238
00:09:30,991 --> 00:09:33,209
- You're funny.
- Dad! Mom!

239
00:09:33,294 --> 00:09:34,450
Come look at this!

240
00:09:34,535 --> 00:09:36,168
Coming, honey.

241
00:09:36,427 --> 00:09:38,442
- It was so nice to meet you.
- You too.

242
00:09:38,668 --> 00:09:40,695
You guys are like
the perfect family.

243
00:09:41,998 --> 00:09:43,176
- All right, bye.
- Bye.

244
00:09:43,260 --> 00:09:44,911
- See ya.
- Bye.

